<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-07-06T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-07-06T09:00:00-05:00" n="170" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d170">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/668</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Denmark</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_EMF1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Egan</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-07-06T15:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 6, 1917, 3 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received July 7, 12.10
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>818. <hi rend="italic">Deutsche Tageszeitung</hi>, July 3, quotes
                                from a speech on June 30 by Wolfgang Heine, a member of the
                                Reichstag: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>I recently had a conversation with the Chancellor and I am in
                                        a position to state that he would be willing to conclude
                                        peace towards East and West to-day without any annexations
                                        or compensations. In the past the Chancellor has never
                                        asserted this with such distinctness to the public. He has
                                        considered it more appropriate to keep quiet. This is not
                                        owing to lack of earnestness but to the nature of his
                                        position.</p>
                                </quote>
                            </p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_EMF1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Egan</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>